Burn the book.

You need something in `recurse` to *block* the recursion. Something like

    if (count &lt; 10){
        recurse(count + 1);
    }

Technically the behaviour on your not doing something like that is *undefined* as eventually the `int` will overflow. It&#39;s the fact that you have undefined behaviour on all execution paths that means it&#39;s impossible to say much about the error: an aggressive compiler will compile your code to `int main(){}` as it&#39;s allowed to assume that undefined behaviour cannot happen. A compiler with run-of-the-mill optimisation settings may well unroll the recursion to an infinite loop.

With compiler optimisations suppressed, you&#39;ll hit upon a runtime constraint such as a stack overflow before the `int` limit is reached. That probably manifests itself as the segmentation fault you observe, or some other issuance from the C++ runtime library / operating system. The C++ standard does not specify the error that should emanate.

